The pre-initiative snapshot is empty, so I'll reason from the described stack (Next.js 16, Payload CMS 3, Tailwind CSS 4, Elan design system) and the symptoms you've described precisely. Let me reconstruct the full picture from first principles and give you a complete, surgical fix.

---

## Diagnosis

Two distinct problems, one shared root:

| # | Symptom | Signal |
|---|---------|--------|
| 1 | **36 `<strong>` spans** scattered across 7 body sections | Markdown scan anchors like `"Per user."`, `"Scaffolding."` were authored in bold and the Lexical → HTML serialiser faithfully emits `<strong>` for every one. The prose renderer applies no opinion about *semantic weight* — it just passes formatting through. |
| 2 | **No visual hierarchy between sections** | The section headings (likely `h2`/`h3` rendered by the same serialiser) have insufficient space budget above them, or the Tailwind prose plugin is not configured/applied, so headings and body paragraphs run at nearly the same visual weight and rhythm. |

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 — "Garbage-in typography"**: when user-supplied source content carries inline formatting that was intended as a *reading aid for the author* (scan anchors, draft markers), a system with no strip-or-demote layer will render that authoring noise verbatim into the published UI. The fix must live in the **rendering layer**, not in the CMS content, so future re-imports are also clean.

**CAP-016 — "Unstyled prose container"**: Tailwind CSS resets all browser UA styles. Unless the article body element is wrapped in a `prose` class (or the Elan equivalent), headings render at the same size as body copy, `<strong>` carries no weight calibration, and inter-section spacing collapses.

---

## Fix

The work spans three files:

### 1. `components/RichText/serialize.tsx` — strip decorative bold, demote section-anchor bold to a span

This is the Lexical node serialiser. Add a filter in the `IS_BOLD` branch that detects "scan-anchor" bold (short text, ends in period or colon, stands alone in its paragraph) and renders it as a semantic `<strong>` only when the surrounding paragraph has substantive content. Otherwise emit a plain `<span>`.

```tsx
// components/RichText/serialize.tsx

import escapeHTML from 'escape-html'
import { Fragment } from 'react'
import type { SerializedLexicalNode } from 'lexical'

// ─── Heuristic: is this bold node a scan-anchor / draft marker? ───────────────
// Criteria: text ≤ 40 chars, trimmed text ends with "." or ":", entire
// paragraph contains ONLY this bold node (i.e. it is the sole leaf).
function isScanAnchor(text: string, isOnlyLeafInParagraph: boolean): boolean {
  const t = text.trim()
  return (
    isOnlyLeafInParagraph &&
    t.length <= 40 &&
    (t.endsWith('.') || t.endsWith(':'))
  )
}

export function serializeLexical(nodes: SerializedLexicalNode[]): JSX.Element {
  return (
    <Fragment>
      {nodes.map((node, i) => {
        if (node.type === 'text') {
          const { text, format } = node as any
          const IS_BOLD      = (format & 1) !== 0
          const IS_ITALIC    = (format & 2) !== 0
          const IS_UNDERLINE = (format & 8) !== 0
          const IS_CODE      = (format & 16) !== 0

          let el: JSX.Element = <>{escapeHTML(text)}</>

          if (IS_CODE)      el = <code>{el}</code>
          if (IS_ITALIC)    el = <em>{el}</em>
          if (IS_UNDERLINE) el = <span className="underline">{el}</span>

          // ── Bold gate ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
          // DO NOT wrap in <strong> when the node looks like a scan anchor.
          // The parent paragraph context is threaded in via a closure below.
          if (IS_BOLD) {
            const parentOnlyHasThisLeaf =
              (node as any).__parentLeafCount === 1
            if (isScanAnchor(text, parentOnlyHasThisLeaf)) {
              // Demote: render as styled subheading token, not semantic bold
              el = (
                <span
                  key={i}
                  className="block mt-8 mb-1 text-xs font-medium uppercase tracking-widest text-neutral-400 dark:text-neutral-500"
                >
                  {escapeHTML(text)}
                </span>
              )
              return el
            }
            el = <strong>{el}</strong>
          }

          return <Fragment key={i}>{el}</Fragment>
        }

        // ── Paragraph ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
        if (node.type === 'paragraph') {
          const children = (node as any).children ?? []

          // Annotate each leaf with its sibling count so the bold gate works
          const annotated = children.map((child: any) => ({
            ...child,
            __parentLeafCount: children.length,
          }))

          const serialized = serializeLexical(annotated)

          // A paragraph that contains ONLY a scan-anchor span should not also
          // receive <p> padding — the span itself handles spacing.
          const isScanParagraph =
            children.length === 1 &&
            children[0].type === 'text' &&
            (children[0].format & 1) !== 0 &&
            isScanAnchor(children[0].text, true)

          if (isScanParagraph) return <Fragment key={i}>{serialized}</Fragment>

          return <p key={i}>{serialized}</p>
        }

        // ── Headings ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
        if (node.type === 'heading') {
          const tag = (node as any).tag // 'h1' | 'h2' | 'h3' …
          const Tag = tag as keyof JSX.IntrinsicElements
          return (
            <Tag key={i}>
              {serializeLexical((node as any).children)}
            </Tag>
          )
        }

        // … other node types (list, listitem, link, quote) remain unchanged
        return null
      })}
    </Fragment>
  )
}
```

> **Key mechanics**: `__parentLeafCount` is a one-line annotation threaded onto each text node from its parent paragraph before recursion. No global state, no second pass.

---

### 2. `app/(frontend)/articles/[slug]/page.tsx` — wrap the article body in the prose container

```tsx
// app/(frontend)/articles/[slug]/page.tsx  (body section only, abbreviated)

import { serializeLexical } from '@/components/RichText/serialize'

export default async function ArticlePage({ params }: { params: { slug: string } }) {
  const article = await getArticleBySlug(params.slug) // your existing fetch

  return (
    <article className="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-4 py-16">
      <header className="mb-12">
        <h1 className="text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-50">
          {article.title}
        </h1>
        {/* byline, date, tags… */}
      </header>

      {article.bodies.map((body, i) => (
        <section
          key={i}
          className={[
            // ── Section separation ─────────────────────────────────────────
            // Each body section gets a top border + generous top padding.
            // First section skips the border (it follows the header directly).
            i === 0
              ? 'pt-0'
              : 'mt-16 pt-10 border-t border-neutral-200 dark:border-neutral-800',

            // ── Prose type scale ───────────────────────────────────────────
            // Tailwind Typography plugin gives headings, paragraphs, lists,
            // <strong>, <em>, <code> a calibrated vertical rhythm.
            // prose-neutral keeps the palette neutral; prose-lg for
            // comfortable reading measure at max-w-2xl.
            'prose prose-lg prose-neutral dark:prose-invert',

            // ── Bold re-calibration inside prose ──────────────────────────
            // Tailwind prose makes <strong> font-weight:600. That is still
            // heavy for a 36-instance document. Drop it to 500 (medium)
            // so genuinely semantic bold is present but not shouty.
            'prose-strong:font-medium prose-strong:text-neutral-800 dark:prose-strong:text-neutral-200',

            // ── Heading rhythm inside each section ────────────────────────
            'prose-headings:font-semibold prose-headings:tracking-tight',
            'prose-h2:text-2xl prose-h2:mt-10 prose-h2:mb-4',
            'prose-h3:text-lg prose-h3:mt-8 prose-h3:mb-2',
          ].join(' ')}
        >
          {serializeLexical(body.richText.root.children)}
        </section>
      ))}
    </article>
  )
}
```

---

### 3. `tailwind.config.ts` — ensure the Typography plugin is loaded and prose is not purged

```ts
// tailwind.config.ts
import type { Config } from 'tailwindcss'
import typography from '@tailwindcss/typography'   // npm i -D @tailwindcss/typography

const config: Config = {
  content: [
    './app/**/*.{ts,tsx}',
    './components/**/*.{ts,tsx}',
  ],
  plugins: [typography],
  theme: {
    extend: {
      typography: ({ theme }: { theme: (path: string) => string }) => ({
        DEFAULT: {
          css: {
            // Calibrate base <strong> weight globally so even
            // markdown-imported content never screams.
            strong: {
              fontWeight: theme('fontWeight.medium'),   // 500, not 700
            },
            // Give h2 enough top margin to feel like a real section break.
            h2: {
              marginTop: theme('spacing.12'),
              paddingTop: theme('spacing.2'),
            },
          },
        },
      }),
    },
  },
}

export default config
```

---

## What each change does, end-to-end

```
CMS Lexical JSON
      │
      ▼
serializeLexical()                          ← File 1
  ├─ text node, IS_BOLD=true
  │    ├─ isScanAnchor? (≤40 chars, ends ".", lone leaf)
  │    │    YES → <span class="…tracking-widest text-neutral-400…">
  │    │           paragraph wrapper suppressed   ← 36 offenders gone
  │    │    NO  → <strong>…</strong>              ← genuine semantic bold kept
  │    └─ (italic, code, underline unchanged)
  └─ paragraph, heading, list… unchanged
      │
      ▼
<section class="prose prose-lg … mt-16 pt-10 border-t …">  ← File 2
  │   Tailwind Typography owns the type scale.
  │   Border-top + mt-16 creates hard visual break between bodies.
  │   prose-strong:font-medium tames any residual <strong>.
  └─ First body: no border (follows header directly).
      │
      ▼
tailwind.config.ts                          ← File 3
  typography.DEFAULT.css.strong.fontWeight = 500
  typography.DEFAULT.css.h2.marginTop      = 3rem
```

---

## Principle

**Rendering layers must express editorial intent, not authoring noise.** A serialiser that is a transparent pass-through of format bits is correct for a generic CMS widget; it is wrong for a curated long-form essay renderer. The fix introduces a single, well-bounded heuristic at the serialiser boundary — short, period-terminated, paragraph-sole bold nodes are *scan anchors*, not *emphasis* — and demotes them to a typographically quiet label token. Genuine `<strong>` emphasis (mid-sentence, in mixed-leaf paragraphs) is left completely untouched. Section hierarchy is then enforced structurally (`border-t` + generous margin between `<section>` elements) and typographically (`prose` plugin calibrating the heading scale), so it cannot be accidentally collapsed by future content changes.
